{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584445"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:46:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:46:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14522"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14522"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.16,0.05,0.26,0.39]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7217"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114390"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7217","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7217"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14522"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96391"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6685"},{"type":"tags","id":"6884"},{"type":"tags","id":"6888"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17513"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17514"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114390"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is an unpaired, visceral branch of the thoracic aorta?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Posterior intercostal arteries","Superior phrenic arteries","Bronchial arteries","Oesophageal arteries","Median sacral artery"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe thoracic aorta\u0027s branches are parietal (supplying the thoracic wall) or visceral (supplying thoracic organs). Some are paired, while others are unpaired.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoesophageal artery\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer, as it is an unpaired, visceral branch of the thoracic aorta. These arteries (typically four to five in number) arise directly from the anterior aspect of the thoracic aorta and supply the oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior intercostal arteries\u003C/strong\u003E are paired, parietal branches of the thoracic aorta that supply the intercostal spaces. There are typically nine pairs, supplying the lower nine intercostal spaces.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior phrenic arteries\u003C/strong\u003E are paired, visceral branches that supply the superior surface of the diaphragm. They arise from the lower part of the thoracic aorta.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebronchial arteries\u003C/strong\u003E are typically paired (two left and one right), visceral branches that supply the bronchi, lung tissue, and visceral pleura. They provide oxygenated blood to the lungs, complementing the pulmonary arteries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian sacral artery\u003C/strong\u003E is an unpaired, parietal branch, but it arises from the abdominal aorta, not the thoracic aorta. It descends in the midline over the lumbar vertebrae and sacrum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther unpaired, visceral branches of the thoracic aorta include small pericardial and mediastinal branches. The thoracic aorta also gives rise to paired subcostal arteries, which are similar to the posterior intercostal arteries but supply the subcostal region.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The oesophageal artery branches from the thoracic aorta, and is the unpaired, visceral branch.","The thoracic aorta gives rise to both paired and unpaired branches that supply thoracic structures.","Branches of the thoracic aorta can be classified as parietal (supplying the thoracic wall) or visceral (supplying thoracic organs)."],"references":["Netter, F. H. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: Classic Regional Approach-Ebook. 2022. Elsevier Health Sciences","Shahoud JS, Miao JH, Bolla SR. Anatomy, Thorax, Heart Aorta. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538140/","Jacob, S. (2007). Human anatomy: a clinically-orientated approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dagenais F. Anatomy of the thoracic aorta and of its branches. Thorac Surg Clin. 2011 May;21(2):219-27, viii. doi: 10.1016/j.thorsurg.2010.12.004. PMID: 21477772."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96391"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14522"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96391"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-16T10:26:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-16T10:26:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7217"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114390"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemC